## Student Activism and The Arrival of Herman Hudson

THough this visual narrative centers on Herman Hudson's role in being the founding Chancellor for Afro-Affairs in 1970 as well as the founding chair of the deparment of Afro-American Studies, both of which greatly helped to change the face of Indiana UNiversit, this digital collection also centers the pivotal role that Black student activists played in being the fundemental initators of the insitutional shifts and creators of the conditions that created a space for Hudson to occupy those positions. As such student voices are move to the fore here through student publications and such. It also proves valuable to provide some biographical information on Hudson and how he came to IU. 1968 pivot year

